<article>
    <h1>Adopt&#xAD;ing real-time safety mea&#xAD;sures</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-09"><time>2020-11-09</time></a>
        - <span>PLACE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>BHCC Con­struc­tion has var­i­ous mea­sures in place to achieve min­i­mal dis­rup­tions and max­i­mum pro­duc­tiv­ity</p>
    <p>An elec­tronic sys­tem for its per­mit to work, daily in­spec­tion, tool box meet­ing, and more — these al­low the com­pany’s Work­place Safety and Health (WSH) of­fi­cers, en­gi­neers and man­agers to as­sess safety and health pro­vi­sions in real time via their smart­phones while they make their rounds on site, says its project direc­tor Andy Koh.</p>
    <p>Also, its near miss re­port­ing (an un­planned event that did not re­sult in in­jury) in­volves the anal­y­sis of col­lated statis­tics from all projects in var­i­ous as­pects and at­tributes. “This al­lows us to in­tro­duce ap­pro­pri­ate re-train­ing pro­grammes or en­hance mit­i­ga­tion mea­sures be­fore an ac­ci­dent takes place,” he explains.</p>
    <p>To re­duce health risks and sup­port work­ers, the com­pany is also part­ner­ing ven­dors to adopt ad­vanced tech­nolo­gies such as ther­mal scan­ners, ar­ti­fi­cial in­tel­li­gence cam­eras, safe-dis­tanc­ing to­kens and more.</p>
    <p>“With these in place, we can bet­ter man­age and mon­i­tor our work­force on-site to en­sure the risk of Covid-19 virus trans­mis­sion is mit­i­gated ef­fec­tively,” says its QEHS direc­tor Joseph Chua.</p>

